WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.840 --> 00:00:05.055
Professor John Rogers:
The best way,

00:00:05.055 --> 00:00:09.040
I think, to introduce the
central issues of this wonderful

00:00:09.040 --> 00:00:12.816
poem, "Lycidas,"
is to return to Milton's

00:00:12.816 --> 00:00:17.220
Comus. So yet once
more -- and I promise this will

00:00:17.220 --> 00:00:21.694
be one of the last times that we
look back at Milton's mask --

00:00:21.694 --> 00:00:25.610
but yet once more,
let's look at Comus.

00:00:25.610 --> 00:00:28.689
Now you will remember that
the mask Comus was

00:00:28.689 --> 00:00:31.656
everywhere concerned with
questions of the power of --

00:00:31.656 --> 00:00:33.545
well,
the strangely intertwined

00:00:33.545 --> 00:00:36.705
questions of the power of
chastity on the one hand and the

00:00:36.705 --> 00:00:40.452
power of poetry on the other.
The two brothers in the mask

00:00:40.452 --> 00:00:44.115
engaged in that philosophical
debate about the force,

00:00:44.115 --> 00:00:46.440
or the strength,
of virginity.

00:00:46.440 --> 00:00:47.921
The Second Brother,
you'll remember,

00:00:47.921 --> 00:00:50.630
had taken what I take to be the
perfectly reasonable position,

00:00:50.630 --> 00:00:53.483
the cautious position,
that the Lady is in danger --

00:00:53.483 --> 00:00:59.375
that she's a sitting duck,
in fact, out there in the

00:00:59.375 --> 00:01:04.099
dangerous forest.
According to the Second

00:01:04.099 --> 00:01:07.390
Brother, it's virtually
impossible for a single,

00:01:07.390 --> 00:01:10.610
helpless maiden to pass
uninjured in this wild,

00:01:10.610 --> 00:01:13.466
surrounding waste.
Now the Elder Brother,

00:01:13.466 --> 00:01:15.903
we remember,
hastily dismissed his brother's

00:01:15.903 --> 00:01:18.584
pessimism,
and then he insisted that the

00:01:18.584 --> 00:01:22.339
Lady's virginity was fully
capable of protecting her from

00:01:22.339 --> 00:01:26.027
any such physical attack.Now
to the extent that this

00:01:26.027 --> 00:01:30.251
discussion is actually about the
virginity of the Second Brother

00:01:30.251 --> 00:01:34.864
and the Elder Brother's sister,
it seems, I think,

00:01:34.864 --> 00:01:39.116
to border on the ridiculous;
but the debate,

00:01:39.116 --> 00:01:41.340
I think, we have to take
seriously.

00:01:41.340 --> 00:01:43.984
It's an important one for
Milton, and it's important

00:01:43.984 --> 00:01:47.200
because it touches on a lot of
more consequential questions.

00:01:47.200 --> 00:01:53.348
I'm thinking of the general
problem of the abstraction of

00:01:53.348 --> 00:01:57.629
virtue, an abstract notion of
virtue.

00:01:57.629 --> 00:02:02.762
Think of all the questions that
all of us at some point or other

00:02:02.762 --> 00:02:07.372
tend to associate with virtue.
Is virtuous behavior repaid

00:02:07.372 --> 00:02:11.770
with some kind of ultimate good?
Are we rewarded for our virtue

00:02:11.770 --> 00:02:16.012
and for our virtuous deeds?
Are we recompensed in some way

00:02:16.012 --> 00:02:21.180
for all of those sacrifices that
we make in the name of virtue?

00:02:21.180 --> 00:02:24.971
These are questions that Milton
will never stop asking and that

00:02:24.971 --> 00:02:27.539
he will never stop attempting to
answer.

00:02:27.539 --> 00:02:31.417
The position that Milton --
this is how I like to read it --

00:02:31.417 --> 00:02:35.425
the position that Milton would
like to be able to take on this

00:02:35.425 --> 00:02:39.434
question of virtue's reward is
formulated by the Elder Brother

00:02:39.434 --> 00:02:42.385
in Comus.
I'm thinking of the passage

00:02:42.385 --> 00:02:44.949
near the bottom of page 103 in
the Hughes.

00:02:44.949 --> 00:02:48.465
This is Comus,
line 588 -- the Elder

00:02:48.465 --> 00:02:50.400
Brother.
The brother says: 

00:02:50.400 --> 00:02:54.657
Virtue may be assail'd
but never hurt, Surpris'd by

00:02:54.657 --> 00:02:58.677
unjust force but not enthrall'd,
 Yea even that which

00:02:58.677 --> 00:03:02.562
mischief meant most harm
Shall in the happy trial prove

00:03:02.562 --> 00:03:06.134
most glory.
But evil on itself shall back

00:03:06.134 --> 00:03:11.311
recoil And mix no more with
goodness, when at last

00:03:11.311 --> 00:03:15.878
Gather'd like scum,
and settl'd to itself, It

00:03:15.878 --> 00:03:20.394
shall be in eternal restless
change Self-fed and

00:03:20.394 --> 00:03:24.669
self-consum'd;
if this fail, The pillar'd

00:03:24.669 --> 00:03:29.560
firmament is rott'nness, And
earth's base built on

00:03:29.560 --> 00:03:32.819
stubble.
Virtue invariably protects

00:03:32.819 --> 00:03:35.487
itself.
Virtue is invariably rewarded

00:03:35.487 --> 00:03:40.080
with glory and evil -- and this
is the flip side of the coin --

00:03:40.080 --> 00:03:44.051
evil is always punished.
In this amazing image,

00:03:44.051 --> 00:03:49.248
it's gathered like scum in some
eternal cesspool where it's

00:03:49.248 --> 00:03:53.550
self-fed and self-consumed --
problem solved!

00:03:53.550 --> 00:03:58.149
The Elder Brother continues,
though, "if this fail" -- by

00:03:58.149 --> 00:04:01.598
which he means,
if virtue does not in every

00:04:01.598 --> 00:04:04.719
single instance triumph over
evil,

00:04:04.719 --> 00:04:07.536
then this is a world whose
heaven, whose pillared

00:04:07.536 --> 00:04:09.590
firmament, is rotten to the
core,

00:04:09.590 --> 00:04:12.285
and whose base,
or whose very foundation,

00:04:12.285 --> 00:04:16.469
is nothing but stubble.
If virtue fails to triumph over

00:04:16.469 --> 00:04:20.699
evil, then what?
Then this simply isn't a world

00:04:20.699 --> 00:04:24.316
worth living in.
That's what I take the Elder

00:04:24.316 --> 00:04:28.879
Brother to mean here.These
are unquestionably strong words,

00:04:28.879 --> 00:04:34.934
and I think it's impossible for
us to overestimate the weight of

00:04:34.934 --> 00:04:38.053
these words.
The speech is more than just a

00:04:38.053 --> 00:04:40.891
pious bit of optimism like a lot
of the speeches,

00:04:40.891 --> 00:04:43.730
in fact, that the other brother
has given us.

00:04:43.730 --> 00:04:46.250
We have to confess that it's
more than that.

00:04:46.250 --> 00:04:50.102
This speech is a challenge.
The Elder Brother is

00:04:50.102 --> 00:04:54.420
challenging God to see to it
that some kind of justice is

00:04:54.420 --> 00:04:59.294
actually effected on this earth;
and so I'm going to be placing

00:04:59.294 --> 00:05:03.787
a particular amount of pressure
on this passage because this is

00:05:03.787 --> 00:05:07.990
the first expression in Milton
of a very particular kind of

00:05:07.990 --> 00:05:12.161
argument: a religious argument,
and it's one that becomes

00:05:12.161 --> 00:05:14.410
central to all of Paradise
Lost.

00:05:14.410 --> 00:05:18.790
The speech of the Elder
Brothers is a theodicy.

00:05:18.790 --> 00:05:22.730
Theodicy is the term
coined by the eighteenth-century

00:05:22.730 --> 00:05:25.812
philosopher Leibniz,
and he applied this term

00:05:25.812 --> 00:05:29.777
theodicy to just that
kind of philosophical sentiment

00:05:29.777 --> 00:05:34.439
that's implied by its etymology.
The theodicy is an account of

00:05:34.439 --> 00:05:38.660
the justice (the dike) of
God (theos).

00:05:38.660 --> 00:05:41.491
And so, to use the words with
which Milton would begin

00:05:41.491 --> 00:05:44.665
Paradise Lost,
a theodicy is an attempt "to

00:05:44.665 --> 00:05:48.207
justify the ways of God to
men."Now for a lot of

00:05:48.207 --> 00:05:52.445
orthodox Christians in Milton's
time -- and I think we can say

00:05:52.445 --> 00:05:56.752
the same for a lot of orthodox
Christians in our own time -- to

00:05:56.752 --> 00:06:00.156
embark upon anything like a
theodicy at all can be

00:06:00.156 --> 00:06:04.740
considered heretical,
or at the very least heterodox.

00:06:04.740 --> 00:06:08.425
A theodicy can be seen as
heretical or even blasphemous

00:06:08.425 --> 00:06:12.519
for the simple reason that it --
think of what it assumes.

00:06:12.519 --> 00:06:17.769
It assumes that the ways of God
are in fact justifiable.

00:06:17.769 --> 00:06:22.155
A theodicy assumes that God's
justice can be witnessed,

00:06:22.155 --> 00:06:25.810
that it can be accounted for
here on earth.

00:06:25.810 --> 00:06:30.547
A theodicy assumes that things
on earth actually make sense and

00:06:30.547 --> 00:06:34.750
that God's ways are ultimately
rationally accessible,

00:06:34.750 --> 00:06:37.326
that they are comprehensible by
human beings,

00:06:37.326 --> 00:06:40.019
and that God can in some way --
and this is,

00:06:40.019 --> 00:06:43.368
I think, the central
implication of the Elder Brother

00:06:43.368 --> 00:06:47.167
here -- that God can in some way
be held accountable for his

00:06:47.167 --> 00:06:49.748
actions.
To justify the ways of God to

00:06:49.748 --> 00:06:53.551
men is essentially to put God on
trial for the actions that he

00:06:53.551 --> 00:06:56.398
performs.
Of course in the central test

00:06:56.398 --> 00:07:00.377
case this is what we all care
about, for the unfortunate

00:07:00.377 --> 00:07:04.501
events that befall virtuous
people.The next major poem

00:07:04.501 --> 00:07:08.335
that Milton writes after
Comus is "Lycidas."

00:07:08.335 --> 00:07:13.399
You'll remember that Milton
published Comus in 1637.

00:07:13.399 --> 00:07:17.440
It's 1637, later that same
year, that Milton writes

00:07:17.440 --> 00:07:20.495
"Lycidas."
In "Lycidas," Milton

00:07:20.495 --> 00:07:23.740
looks back at the Elder
Brother's theodicy,

00:07:23.740 --> 00:07:28.529
and it's almost as if he's
attempting to test its validity.

00:07:28.529 --> 00:07:32.092
You can figure Milton asking in
this poem "Lycidas" if it's

00:07:32.092 --> 00:07:34.980
true: is it true what the Elder
Brother said,

00:07:34.980 --> 00:07:39.779
that virtue is always rewarded
and evil punished?

00:07:39.779 --> 00:07:42.946
Now "Lycidas," and this
is undeniable,

00:07:42.946 --> 00:07:46.184
is ostensibly,
and maybe more than ostensibly,

00:07:46.184 --> 00:07:49.920
an elegy.
It's a poem about a death.

00:07:49.920 --> 00:07:54.699
It mourns the loss of a friend
of Milton's from Cambridge.

00:07:54.699 --> 00:07:58.493
The young man was named Edward
King, and he drowned in a

00:07:58.493 --> 00:08:02.494
shipwreck in the Irish Sea
shortly before he took up orders

00:08:02.494 --> 00:08:05.529
as a minister for the Church of
England.

00:08:05.529 --> 00:08:08.063
Like so many -- and I mentioned
this before -- like so many of

00:08:08.063 --> 00:08:10.139
the young men studying with
Milton in Cambridge,

00:08:10.139 --> 00:08:13.629
King was being prepared to
pursue a career in the

00:08:13.629 --> 00:08:16.536
church.Now,
and I don't think this is

00:08:16.536 --> 00:08:20.461
unimportant,
King was also -- it would seem

00:08:20.461 --> 00:08:24.420
he was also a minor poet,
an amateur poet.

00:08:24.420 --> 00:08:29.690
Like Milton, he wrote verses.
There is nothing like a shred

00:08:29.690 --> 00:08:33.985
of evidence to suggest that
Edward King had any talent

00:08:33.985 --> 00:08:35.765
whatsoever.
Nonetheless,

00:08:35.765 --> 00:08:38.349
the fact that he attempted to
be a poet, I think,

00:08:38.349 --> 00:08:40.452
is important here.
Edward King,

00:08:40.452 --> 00:08:44.746
in fact, seems to have been
sufficiently well liked or

00:08:44.746 --> 00:08:49.039
admired that when news of his
death hit Cambridge,

00:08:49.039 --> 00:08:52.192
a group of his friends
organized something like an

00:08:52.192 --> 00:08:55.509
anthology of poems in his honor.
This is on the handout.

00:08:55.509 --> 00:09:00.379
The title of the book is
Justa Eduardo King naufrago,

00:09:00.379 --> 00:09:05.250
Obsequies on Edward King,
Lost at Sea or Drowned.

00:09:05.250 --> 00:09:10.320
We have no evidence that King
was a particularly close friend

00:09:10.320 --> 00:09:14.800
of Milton's, but nonetheless
Milton -- as an ambitious

00:09:14.800 --> 00:09:19.919
literary figure in college,
he was asked to contribute some

00:09:19.919 --> 00:09:24.032
verses to the anthology,
and "Lycidas" is the

00:09:24.032 --> 00:09:28.461
product of that request.
We shouldn't be surprised that

00:09:28.461 --> 00:09:31.990
Milton has to be compelled to
write this poem.

00:09:31.990 --> 00:09:35.882
He's still in that awkward
phase of unreadiness and under

00:09:35.882 --> 00:09:40.052
preparation.Now readers have
always seemed to have agreed

00:09:40.052 --> 00:09:43.945
that Milton's "Lycidas"
is an enormously admirable

00:09:43.945 --> 00:09:46.992
poem,
but for a few hundred years now

00:09:46.992 --> 00:09:51.041
there has been a controversy
over how admirable Milton's

00:09:51.041 --> 00:09:54.360
"Lycidas" is,
specifically as an elegy.

00:09:54.360 --> 00:09:56.710
The poem is obviously
magisterial.

00:09:56.710 --> 00:10:01.876
It's moving and just about
everyone concedes that at many

00:10:01.876 --> 00:10:06.951
junctures it's extraordinarily
learned -- it's obviously

00:10:06.951 --> 00:10:10.549
learned, but it's also very
moving.

00:10:10.549 --> 00:10:14.110
This is the question now:
is it properly elegiac?

00:10:14.110 --> 00:10:18.023
Is "Lycidas" an appropriate
expression of grief over the

00:10:18.023 --> 00:10:21.054
death of Edward King,
and furthermore,

00:10:21.054 --> 00:10:25.935
does it console others for
their grief over Edward King's

00:10:25.935 --> 00:10:28.290
death?
Now this is a debate that fits

00:10:28.290 --> 00:10:30.750
into the same category,
as far as I'm concerned,

00:10:30.750 --> 00:10:33.629
as the one between the elder
and the Second Brother.

00:10:33.629 --> 00:10:39.200
This is a debate that will
forever and forever be fruitless

00:10:39.200 --> 00:10:42.735
because it's unanswerable.
Nonetheless,

00:10:42.735 --> 00:10:46.469
I still think there's something
about this controversy

00:10:46.469 --> 00:10:50.697
surrounding this poem -- the
poem as an elegy -- that we need

00:10:50.697 --> 00:10:53.992
to take as instructive;
because if Milton's

00:10:53.992 --> 00:10:57.679
"Lycidas" isn't an
expression of grief over the

00:10:57.679 --> 00:11:02.143
death of Edward King,
then just what -- this is what

00:11:02.143 --> 00:11:07.450
we have to ask -- then just what
is it an expression of?

00:11:07.450 --> 00:11:12.549
So let us begin our
examination of this question

00:11:12.549 --> 00:11:16.950
with the consideration of the
poem's form.

00:11:16.950 --> 00:11:20.648
Now the most distinguishing
feature of Milton's elegy is the

00:11:20.648 --> 00:11:25.270
fact that it's a pastoral elegy.
It engages the ancient art of

00:11:25.270 --> 00:11:30.338
pastoral poetry initiated and
made famous by the great Greek

00:11:30.338 --> 00:11:34.043
poet Theocritus,
which was later imitated by

00:11:34.043 --> 00:11:38.191
Moscus and then finally by the
Roman poet Virgil in his

00:11:38.191 --> 00:11:42.658
celebrated pastoral eclogues.
You can see on the handout

00:11:42.658 --> 00:11:46.599
those poems by those classical
authors that Milton's

00:11:46.599 --> 00:11:49.690
"Lycidas" is most
indebted to.

00:11:49.690 --> 00:11:53.280
The pastoral elegy is clearly
one of the most stylized and

00:11:53.280 --> 00:11:57.250
most self-consciously artificial
of all of the poetic genres.

00:11:57.250 --> 00:12:01.394
The poet of a pastoral elegy
usually represents himself as a

00:12:01.394 --> 00:12:05.820
shepherd, a shepherd mourning
the death of a fellow shepherd,

00:12:05.820 --> 00:12:09.401
and he often explains that the
death of his shepherd friend is

00:12:09.401 --> 00:12:12.690
exerting a magical effect on the
entire natural world.

00:12:12.690 --> 00:12:14.139
This is called the pathetic
fallacy.

00:12:14.139 --> 00:12:17.587
The trees, the rocks,
and the streams are all weeping

00:12:17.587 --> 00:12:20.571
for the loss of the
shepherd-speaker's beloved

00:12:20.571 --> 00:12:23.149
companion.
It's at this point in the

00:12:23.149 --> 00:12:25.392
pastoral elegy -- the
conventional,

00:12:25.392 --> 00:12:29.416
stereotypical pastoral elegy --
that the poet-shepherd sings a

00:12:29.416 --> 00:12:32.874
mournful song.
He sings a song in which he

00:12:32.874 --> 00:12:37.528
recalls all of those happy days
that he had spent with his

00:12:37.528 --> 00:12:41.692
shepherd friend in the
countryside.So we have in

00:12:41.692 --> 00:12:47.000
the pastoral elegy a generic
form that's highly predictable.

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:49.524
Not only now,
but, I think,

00:12:49.524 --> 00:12:54.960
on some level it has always
struck some of its readers as

00:12:54.960 --> 00:12:58.218
ludicrous.
We're not being merely

00:12:58.218 --> 00:13:02.275
churlish, I think,
if we want to ask why someone

00:13:02.275 --> 00:13:06.159
would want to write a poem in
such a form.

00:13:06.159 --> 00:13:10.389
As you can imagine,
it had long been out of fashion

00:13:10.389 --> 00:13:14.999
in Milton's own day.
The pastoral genre in fact even

00:13:14.999 --> 00:13:17.482
for Theocritus,
its inventor,

00:13:17.482 --> 00:13:22.426
was always highly artificial.
Theocritus knew no more about

00:13:22.426 --> 00:13:25.912
shepherds or sheep or
shepherdesses or nymphs and

00:13:25.912 --> 00:13:29.761
satyrs than you or I know and
later urban poets -- and

00:13:29.761 --> 00:13:34.046
Theocritus was an urban poet
--later urban poets like Virgil

00:13:34.046 --> 00:13:39.130
or Milton (Milton our Londoner)
knew even less than Theocritus,

00:13:39.130 --> 00:13:42.084
we have to assume.
It's almost as if the entire

00:13:42.084 --> 00:13:46.702
point of a pastoral is that it
is set in a world that neither

00:13:46.702 --> 00:13:51.165
the urbane poet nor the urbane
reader has actually any real

00:13:51.165 --> 00:13:54.936
experience with.Another way
into this problem:

00:13:54.936 --> 00:13:57.553
let's look at the comments that
Dr.

00:13:57.553 --> 00:14:01.401
Johnson made about Milton's
"Lycidas" in the

00:14:01.401 --> 00:14:05.879
eighteenth century.
This is reading from the packet

00:14:05.879 --> 00:14:09.309
assigned for today,
and I'm going to ask you to do

00:14:09.309 --> 00:14:13.299
what you can to get through the
biography of Milton in the

00:14:13.299 --> 00:14:16.030
packet,
as well as the notes on

00:14:16.030 --> 00:14:18.990
Milton's poetry that we have
from Dr.

00:14:18.990 --> 00:14:22.517
Samuel Johnson.
Make sure you all have done

00:14:22.517 --> 00:14:24.507
that by the midterm.
Okay.

00:14:24.507 --> 00:14:27.609
Famously, Dr.
Johnson couldn't bear this

00:14:27.609 --> 00:14:32.142
poem, "Lycidas" -- Dr.
Johnson, the greatest of all

00:14:32.142 --> 00:14:35.960
literary critics of the
eighteenth century.

00:14:35.960 --> 00:14:39.069
Because Milton's poem is
probably considered to be the

00:14:39.069 --> 00:14:42.529
most important elegy written in
any language by any poet,

00:14:42.529 --> 00:14:47.169
Johnson's assessment of it has
become famous for being one of

00:14:47.169 --> 00:14:51.191
the most wrong-headed
evaluations ever made of a work

00:14:51.191 --> 00:14:55.444
of literature by a great
literary critic -- but inspired

00:14:55.444 --> 00:14:58.615
wrong-headedness,
which is what I take Dr.

00:14:58.615 --> 00:15:02.250
Johnson to be guilty of,
is invaluable.

00:15:02.250 --> 00:15:04.813
And so I want to quote Dr.
Johnson here,

00:15:04.813 --> 00:15:08.011
and this is on the handout.
["Lycidas"]

00:15:08.011 --> 00:15:12.340
is not to be considered as the
effusion of real passion;

00:15:12.340 --> 00:15:16.734
for passion runs not after
remote allusions and obscure

00:15:16.734 --> 00:15:20.071
opinions.
Passion plucks no berries from

00:15:20.071 --> 00:15:23.816
the myrtle and ivy,
nor calls upon Arethuse and

00:15:23.816 --> 00:15:28.374
Mincius, nor tells of "rough
satyrs and fauns with cloven

00:15:28.374 --> 00:15:31.033
heel."
"Where there is leisure for

00:15:31.033 --> 00:15:33.580
fiction, there is little
grief."

00:15:33.580 --> 00:15:36.721
[The]
form [of the pastoral elegy,

00:15:36.721 --> 00:15:41.070
or the form of "Lycidas"]
is that of a pastoral,

00:15:41.070 --> 00:15:45.500
easy, vulgar and therefore
disgusting…

00:15:45.500 --> 00:15:47.299
Now I have to say,
although the last word is

00:15:47.299 --> 00:15:49.559
obviously incredibly powerful
and sort of wonderful,

00:15:49.559 --> 00:15:52.066
it doesn't have quite the punch
that it does -- it didn't have

00:15:52.066 --> 00:15:54.203
quite the punch in the
eighteenth century that it has

00:15:54.203 --> 00:15:57.191
for us now.
Disgusting really means

00:15:57.191 --> 00:16:00.670
literally for Johnson merely
"distasteful."

00:16:00.670 --> 00:16:04.220
These are still strong words.
There has to be something more

00:16:04.220 --> 00:16:07.943
here than merely Johnson's
massive blunder as a literary

00:16:07.943 --> 00:16:11.029
critic.
Johnson tells us that "Lycidas"

00:16:11.029 --> 00:16:15.460
is not to be considered as the
effusion of real passion,

00:16:15.460 --> 00:16:19.206
for passion runs not after
remote allusions and obscure

00:16:19.206 --> 00:16:22.392
opinions.
It's difficult to imagine that

00:16:22.392 --> 00:16:26.590
as an expression of genuine
grief over the death of a

00:16:26.590 --> 00:16:30.950
genuinely close friend would
take the form of a poem so

00:16:30.950 --> 00:16:33.833
learned,
so filled with remote literary

00:16:33.833 --> 00:16:37.685
allusions and obscure opinions.
Johnson obviously has a point

00:16:37.685 --> 00:16:41.672
here.But we have to remember
that King himself was a poet,

00:16:41.672 --> 00:16:43.960
or thought of himself as a
poet.

00:16:43.960 --> 00:16:47.480
He was a poet who died before
he could take up his career,

00:16:47.480 --> 00:16:51.247
and it's not unlikely that --
he wasn't married -- that he was

00:16:51.247 --> 00:16:54.519
also a poet who died while he
was still a virgin.

00:16:54.519 --> 00:16:58.860
King's death provides Milton
with an occasion on which Milton

00:16:58.860 --> 00:17:02.767
is able to write the most
personal poem that he has yet

00:17:02.767 --> 00:17:06.240
written and perhaps that he will
ever write.

00:17:06.240 --> 00:17:10.522
He gets to ask all of those
questions that are most pressing

00:17:10.522 --> 00:17:13.606
to him, John Milton.
What if the virginal Milton

00:17:13.606 --> 00:17:16.579
were to die before he was able
to take up his career?

00:17:16.579 --> 00:17:21.926
What if he died before he was
able to fulfill his promise as a

00:17:21.926 --> 00:17:27.009
poet, before he could publish or
make public his talent?

00:17:27.009 --> 00:17:30.654
The very structure,
in fact, of Milton's poem here

00:17:30.654 --> 00:17:33.481
is what Dr.
Johnson would be obliged to

00:17:33.481 --> 00:17:38.026
call a remote allusion.
The poem is based most closely

00:17:38.026 --> 00:17:41.995
on Virgil's Tenth Eclogue.
This is the poem in which the

00:17:41.995 --> 00:17:45.250
speaker grieves over a death by
imagining a procession of

00:17:45.250 --> 00:17:48.303
mourners at the funeral.
This really provides the

00:17:48.303 --> 00:17:51.764
central rhetorical base for
Milton's "Lycidas."

00:17:51.764 --> 00:17:54.854
The speaker of the poem
mourns the death of the

00:17:54.854 --> 00:17:58.130
shepherd-poet Lycidas and
describes this parade,

00:17:58.130 --> 00:18:02.347
this procession of mourners who
make their tribute to the

00:18:02.347 --> 00:18:06.791
deceased.So look at line --
I'll run through some of the

00:18:06.791 --> 00:18:09.760
essential sections here.
Lines seventy-six to

00:18:09.760 --> 00:18:12.109
eighty-four.
We have the god of poetry,

00:18:12.109 --> 00:18:15.343
Phoebus Apollo himself,
who makes an appearance,

00:18:15.343 --> 00:18:19.472
and he chides Milton for being
so concerned with earthly fame

00:18:19.472 --> 00:18:22.673
-- more on that later.
Line eighty-eight,

00:18:22.673 --> 00:18:26.329
the next section:
Triton, the herald of the sea.

00:18:26.329 --> 00:18:28.980
He tries to make sense of
Lycidas' death.

00:18:28.980 --> 00:18:33.355
He asks the gods what has
happened to Lycidas and who

00:18:33.355 --> 00:18:38.319
exactly was responsible for the
sinking of Lycidas' ship.

00:18:38.319 --> 00:18:41.759
In the next line four lines,
we have Camus;

00:18:41.759 --> 00:18:44.960
the god of the river Cam
appears.

00:18:44.960 --> 00:18:47.608
He represents Cambridge
University, the alma

00:18:47.608 --> 00:18:51.349
mater, where Edward King and
John Milton had been students.

00:18:51.349 --> 00:18:57.557
And finally at lines 108
through 131, we have Saint

00:18:57.557 --> 00:19:04.099
Peter, he of the pearly gates.
Peter bursts onto the scene.

00:19:04.099 --> 00:19:07.487
Without question he's the most
terrifying of all of the

00:19:07.487 --> 00:19:11.565
mourners, and he gives an angry,
powerful, vitriolic speech

00:19:11.565 --> 00:19:15.980
about the terrible state of
England -- the terrible state of

00:19:15.980 --> 00:19:19.351
the Church of England and,
as a consequence,

00:19:19.351 --> 00:19:22.884
of the terrible state of
England in 1637.So the

00:19:22.884 --> 00:19:26.700
structure of this poem is
unquestionably Virgilian,

00:19:26.700 --> 00:19:29.739
but the sentiments that are
voiced in this poem are

00:19:29.739 --> 00:19:34.400
unquestionably Miltonic,
and we will recognize them.

00:19:34.400 --> 00:19:41.930
Who but Milton could speak the
poem's famous opening lines?

00:19:41.930 --> 00:19:43.880
Turn to the beginning of
"Lycidas."

00:19:43.880 --> 00:19:46.327
Yet once more,
O ye Laurels,

00:19:46.327 --> 00:19:50.630
and once more Ye Myrtles
brown, with Ivy never sere,

00:19:50.630 --> 00:19:54.572
 I come to pluck your
Berries harsh and crude, And

00:19:54.572 --> 00:19:58.391
with forc'd fingers rude,
 Shatter your leaves before

00:19:58.391 --> 00:20:01.124
the mellowing year.
Bitter constraint,

00:20:01.124 --> 00:20:05.382
and sad occasion dear,
Compels me to disturb your

00:20:05.382 --> 00:20:09.313
season due: For Lycidas is
dead, dead ere his

00:20:09.313 --> 00:20:12.632
prime...
Milton is lamenting,

00:20:12.632 --> 00:20:18.009
once again, that Milton has
been compelled to begin writing.

00:20:18.009 --> 00:20:21.069
Edward King had died,
and the editor of the Edward

00:20:21.069 --> 00:20:24.690
King Memorial Anthology has
pressed Milton into service.

00:20:24.690 --> 00:20:28.441
What could the young poet do?
Bitter constraint and sad

00:20:28.441 --> 00:20:31.812
occasion are forcing him to
write, even though,

00:20:31.812 --> 00:20:36.028
of course, he's not yet ready.
The laurels and the myrtles

00:20:36.028 --> 00:20:39.559
that he addresses here are,
of course, the traditional

00:20:39.559 --> 00:20:42.890
plants classically associated
with great poets;

00:20:42.890 --> 00:20:49.113
but for Milton in this passage,
importantly these plants simply

00:20:49.113 --> 00:20:52.913
aren't ripe yet.
Their berries are still harsh

00:20:52.913 --> 00:20:55.910
and crude.
They haven't yet had time to

00:20:55.910 --> 00:20:58.472
develop.
Milton is telling us that he is

00:20:58.472 --> 00:21:01.088
himself in the process,
still in the process,

00:21:01.088 --> 00:21:04.261
of maturing.
He's not yet up to the task of

00:21:04.261 --> 00:21:07.234
a great poem yet.
The only fingers with which

00:21:07.234 --> 00:21:10.562
he'll be able to hold his pen
and write this poem are his

00:21:10.562 --> 00:21:12.938
forced fingers rude.Now
you're right:

00:21:12.938 --> 00:21:15.078
you're right if you have the
[laughs]

00:21:15.078 --> 00:21:19.000
feeling that you've heard a lot
of these same ideas before.

00:21:19.000 --> 00:21:22.414
Milton's nearly twenty-nine
years old when he writes

00:21:22.414 --> 00:21:26.497
"Lycidas." He's making
exactly the same disclaimer that

00:21:26.497 --> 00:21:30.570
he had made in Sonnet Seven.
You remember Sonnet Seven,

00:21:30.570 --> 00:21:34.581
"How Soon Hath Time," the
sonnet that he had written on

00:21:34.581 --> 00:21:38.220
the sad occasion of his
twenty-third birthday.

00:21:38.220 --> 00:21:41.007
Milton had claimed there that
he seemed to have all the

00:21:41.007 --> 00:21:43.019
outward appearances of an adult
male,

00:21:43.019 --> 00:21:47.463
of a man, but "[an]
inward ripeness doth much less

00:21:47.463 --> 00:21:49.838
appear."
His poetic talent,

00:21:49.838 --> 00:21:53.429
his poetic promise,
his poetic ripeness -- it

00:21:53.429 --> 00:21:57.753
hasn't yet burgeoned or made
itself manifest.Well,

00:21:57.753 --> 00:22:01.955
this is six years later.
Six years later when Milton

00:22:01.955 --> 00:22:06.240
writes "Lycidas," he's employing
the same fiction of unreadiness

00:22:06.240 --> 00:22:10.660
and filled with all of the same
anxiety of under-preparedness.

00:22:10.660 --> 00:22:14.846
As in Sonnet Seven,
Milton writes the first verse

00:22:14.846 --> 00:22:19.041
paragraph of this great poem,
"Lycidas" -- the first

00:22:19.041 --> 00:22:21.869
fourteen lines -- in essentially
the form of a sonnet.

00:22:21.869 --> 00:22:25.993
The lines have distinctly a
sonnet rhyme-scheme,

00:22:25.993 --> 00:22:29.556
but look closely.
It's not a perfect sonnet in

00:22:29.556 --> 00:22:32.400
quite the same way that Sonnet
Seven was.

00:22:32.400 --> 00:22:35.788
Look at line number four,
which is so clearly -- simply

00:22:35.788 --> 00:22:38.863
by looking at this,
you can tell it's deficient in

00:22:38.863 --> 00:22:43.240
the number of syllables.
There are only six syllables

00:22:43.240 --> 00:22:46.890
here rather than the
conventional ten.

00:22:46.890 --> 00:22:49.853
It's this line,
"And with forc'd fingers rude"

00:22:49.853 --> 00:22:53.079
-- this is called a broken line
or a half-line,

00:22:53.079 --> 00:22:55.711
and this broken line has been
read, I think,

00:22:55.711 --> 00:22:59.506
rightly as Milton's indication
to his reader that he's not even

00:22:59.506 --> 00:23:02.750
up to the task of writing a
sonnet at this point.

00:23:02.750 --> 00:23:08.242
Anything he writes is going to
be forced, compelled -- and with

00:23:08.242 --> 00:23:13.380
his forced fingers rude he
violates the formal prosodic,

00:23:13.380 --> 00:23:16.460
the metrical,
scheme of his elegy at its very

00:23:16.460 --> 00:23:19.495
opening.
Just like Edward King who died

00:23:19.495 --> 00:23:23.075
before his prime,
Milton has to write this poem

00:23:23.075 --> 00:23:27.434
before his own poetic prime and
so it is with this deeply

00:23:27.434 --> 00:23:31.014
apologetic,
intensely hesitant beginning

00:23:31.014 --> 00:23:36.349
that John Milton opens what many
consider to be the greatest poem

00:23:36.349 --> 00:23:41.185
in the English language.The
fact that the death here in

00:23:41.185 --> 00:23:45.019
"Lycidas" is the death of
a young,

00:23:45.019 --> 00:23:47.828
virginal poet at the very
outset of his career,

00:23:47.828 --> 00:23:50.820
as you can imagine,
resonates in a lot of powerful

00:23:50.820 --> 00:23:53.262
ways.
The very idea that a figure so

00:23:53.262 --> 00:23:56.984
virtuous could have been dealt
such a tragic and early death

00:23:56.984 --> 00:23:59.727
strikes Milton,
or Milton's speaker here,

00:23:59.727 --> 00:24:03.218
as the rankest injustice.
It's this sense of injustice

00:24:03.218 --> 00:24:07.116
that keeps pushing this elegy in
the direction of a theodicy:

00:24:07.116 --> 00:24:09.779
an attempt to justify the ways
of God.

00:24:09.779 --> 00:24:14.155
Milton has to justify or at
least understand this seemingly

00:24:14.155 --> 00:24:17.400
incomprehensible and
unjustifiable event.

00:24:17.400 --> 00:24:21.983
It's this drive to theodicy
that accounts for the poem's

00:24:21.983 --> 00:24:26.880
most painful moments.
Look at line fifty.

00:24:26.880 --> 00:24:31.191
This is where Milton asks the
ocean nymphs where they were

00:24:31.191 --> 00:24:35.805
when Edward King's boat was lost
while crossing the Irish Sea:

00:24:35.805 --> 00:24:39.805
why didn't you do anything?
"Where were ye Nymphs,

00:24:39.805 --> 00:24:43.945
when the remorseless deep /
clos'd o'er the head of your

00:24:43.945 --> 00:24:47.904
lov'd Lycidas?"
If you loved Lycidas so much,

00:24:47.904 --> 00:24:52.578
how could you let him die?
No sooner has the speaker asked

00:24:52.578 --> 00:24:56.640
this question -- and you see
this rhythm, this dynamic,

00:24:56.640 --> 00:24:59.759
appear continually throughout
"Lycidas" -- he asks the

00:24:59.759 --> 00:25:02.880
question, and then immediately
he acknowledges the inadequacy

00:25:02.880 --> 00:25:06.164
of the question.
Look at line fifty-five:

00:25:06.164 --> 00:25:10.493
"Ay me, I fondly dream!
/ Had ye been there -- for what

00:25:10.493 --> 00:25:13.542
could that have done?"
The nymphs, of course,

00:25:13.542 --> 00:25:15.864
are powerless,
and worse than that,

00:25:15.864 --> 00:25:18.390
[laughs]
the nymphs, as we know and of

00:25:18.390 --> 00:25:22.010
course as John Milton knew,
are merely fictions.

00:25:22.010 --> 00:25:24.810
This is all made up.
It's folly to think that we

00:25:24.810 --> 00:25:29.315
have about us protective spirits
who might actually keep us from

00:25:29.315 --> 00:25:33.113
harm.Milton continues:
What could the Muse

00:25:33.113 --> 00:25:36.222
herself that Orpheus bore,
The Muse herself,

00:25:36.222 --> 00:25:40.390
for her enchanting son Whom
Universal nature did lament,

00:25:40.390 --> 00:25:44.666
 When by the rout that made
the hideous roar, His gory

00:25:44.666 --> 00:25:50.009
visage down the stream was sent,
 Down the swift Hebrus to

00:25:50.009 --> 00:25:54.282
the Lesbian shore?
Why after all should we expect

00:25:54.282 --> 00:25:56.579
the nymphs to have helped poor
Lycidas?

00:25:56.579 --> 00:26:00.328
Not even the muse Calliope,
the muse of epic poetry,

00:26:00.328 --> 00:26:04.369
was in a position to avert a
human tragedy like this.

00:26:04.369 --> 00:26:08.352
Calliope hadn't even been able
to save her son,

00:26:08.352 --> 00:26:12.508
the poet Orpheus,
when the terrifying Bacchae had

00:26:12.508 --> 00:26:17.876
torn his body limb from limb --
when the terrifying Bacchae had

00:26:17.876 --> 00:26:23.158
sent his head rolling down the
Hebrus River all the way to the

00:26:23.158 --> 00:26:27.150
Isle of Lesbos.
If you've read "L'Allegro" and

00:26:27.150 --> 00:26:31.018
"Il Penseroso," you know
that the image of the great

00:26:31.018 --> 00:26:35.220
mythological poet Orpheus is
always a loaded one for Milton.

00:26:35.220 --> 00:26:39.179
This is a myth that has and
will continue to haunt Milton

00:26:39.179 --> 00:26:42.856
all the way up through
Paradise Lost.Let's

00:26:42.856 --> 00:26:47.028
have a little review of the
career of the great poet Orpheus

00:26:47.028 --> 00:26:50.140
as we get it certainly in
"L'Allegro" and "Il

00:26:50.140 --> 00:26:54.312
Penseroso." Orpheus was
the poet who had attempted to

00:26:54.312 --> 00:26:57.610
bring his wife,
Eurydice, back from the

00:26:57.610 --> 00:27:01.670
underworld, and he did that by
charming Pluto with his song.

00:27:01.670 --> 00:27:04.842
The attempt failed and,
saddened by Eurydice's death,

00:27:04.842 --> 00:27:08.319
Orpheus spent the rest of his
life avoiding the company of

00:27:08.319 --> 00:27:12.437
women.
He kept himself solitary and

00:27:12.437 --> 00:27:15.269
chaste.
He devoted himself to poetry.

00:27:15.269 --> 00:27:18.962
He sang songs of such beauty
that the entire natural world

00:27:18.962 --> 00:27:21.230
would move and dance in
response.

00:27:21.230 --> 00:27:24.464
This is the story of Orpheus
that we have received up to this

00:27:24.464 --> 00:27:27.348
point in Milton's poetry.
This is the story of the

00:27:27.348 --> 00:27:30.385
empowerment of the poet,
his empowerment through his

00:27:30.385 --> 00:27:34.850
experience of a terrible loss.
Clearly this is a myth that

00:27:34.850 --> 00:27:40.037
Milton is identifying with very
strongly here.But the

00:27:40.037 --> 00:27:45.410
subject of "Lycidas" isn't the
empowerment of the poet.

00:27:45.410 --> 00:27:48.019
