00:30:34.509 --> 00:30:38.647
This poem has amazing ebbs and
flows throughout its entirety,

00:30:38.647 --> 00:30:42.785
but without question this is
one of the most intense personal

00:30:42.785 --> 00:30:46.670
moments in the elegy.
Look at line sixty-four.

00:30:46.670 --> 00:30:51.193
Here we have Milton asking
himself all of those questions,

00:30:51.193 --> 00:30:54.049
all of those vocational
questions,

00:30:54.049 --> 00:30:59.313
that this fact -- the fact of
Edward King's death -- seems to

00:30:59.313 --> 00:31:04.119
open up for him:
Alas!

00:31:04.119 --> 00:31:08.417
What boots it with uncessant
care To tend the homely

00:31:08.417 --> 00:31:12.715
slighted Shepherd's trade,
And strictly meditate the

00:31:12.715 --> 00:31:15.936
thankless Muse?
Were it not better done as

00:31:15.936 --> 00:31:19.877
others use, To sport with
Amaryllis in the shade, Or

00:31:19.877 --> 00:31:22.750
with the tangles of Neaera's
hair?

00:31:22.750 --> 00:31:27.214
I think these lines at this
point -- I'm going to read them

00:31:27.214 --> 00:31:29.824
again.
They're too important simply to

00:31:29.824 --> 00:31:31.549
have been read once:
Alas!

00:31:31.549 --> 00:31:35.498
What boots it with uncessant
care To tend the homely

00:31:35.498 --> 00:31:39.446
slighted Shepherd's trade,
And strictly meditate the

00:31:39.446 --> 00:31:42.481
thankless Muse?
Were it not better done as

00:31:42.481 --> 00:31:46.275
others use, To sport with
Amaryllis in the shade, Or

00:31:46.275 --> 00:31:49.039
with the tangles of Neaera's
hair?

00:31:49.039 --> 00:31:52.941
At this point in our reading of
Milton, I think these lines have

00:31:52.941 --> 00:31:55.930
an amazing impact.
We've spent a couple of weeks

00:31:55.930 --> 00:31:58.949
now reading Milton's
declarations of the importance

00:31:58.949 --> 00:32:03.644
of the shepherd's trade.
This is the vocation of poetry

00:32:03.644 --> 00:32:08.064
in this pastoral lexicon.
You remember he's written his

00:32:08.064 --> 00:32:10.681
father in "Ad Patrem"
that the trade,

00:32:10.681 --> 00:32:14.150
the vocation of poetry -- it
may be homely and slighted in

00:32:14.150 --> 00:32:17.931
his father's eyes,
but it was of course worth all

00:32:17.931 --> 00:32:21.661
of Milton's time,
all of Milton's uncessant care

00:32:21.661 --> 00:32:25.424
and investment.
And now Milton's in the

00:32:25.424 --> 00:32:28.570
position of asking,
"What for?

00:32:28.570 --> 00:32:31.653
What's this all about?
Look what happened to Edward

00:32:31.653 --> 00:32:33.600
King.
What's the point of all of this

00:32:33.600 --> 00:32:36.418
study, all of this work,
all of this self-denial if I

00:32:36.418 --> 00:32:39.886
could just wind up" -- this is a
good question -- if I could just

00:32:39.886 --> 00:32:44.227
wind up dead tomorrow?
And now that I'm thinking of

00:32:44.227 --> 00:32:48.917
it, why deny myself sexually?
Why deny myself physical

00:32:48.917 --> 00:32:52.934
gratification if I could just
instead sport with Amaryllis in

00:32:52.934 --> 00:32:56.349
the shade or with the tangles of
Neaera's hair?"

00:32:56.349 --> 00:32:59.880
And Milton's asking in these
lines not simply about actual

00:32:59.880 --> 00:33:03.349
erotic entanglements -- although
I think that's there,

00:33:03.349 --> 00:33:07.500
a relation with women -- but
it's a question about erotic

00:33:07.500 --> 00:33:10.807
poetry as well.
Why can't he write love poetry,

00:33:10.807 --> 00:33:13.449
secular poetry,
instead of this much more

00:33:13.449 --> 00:33:16.685
disciplined,
much more difficult mode of

00:33:16.685 --> 00:33:21.925
sacred and prophetic poetry that
he seems already to have wedded

00:33:21.925 --> 00:33:25.413
himself to?
What's the point of making life

00:33:25.413 --> 00:33:30.059
so hard for himself?Look
now, and this is on the handout,

00:33:30.059 --> 00:33:33.245
at the letter that Milton had
written to his friend,

00:33:33.245 --> 00:33:35.935
Charles Diodati.
This letter was written at

00:33:35.935 --> 00:33:39.788
nearly the same time that Milton
was writing "Lycidas." He

00:33:39.788 --> 00:33:43.099
wrote -- and this too is in the
packet -- he wrote:

00:33:43.099 --> 00:33:46.586
Listen,
Diodati, but in secret lest thy

00:33:46.586 --> 00:33:51.340
blush, and let me talk to you
grandiloquently for a while.

00:33:51.340 --> 00:33:56.410
You ask what I am thinking.
So help me, God,

00:33:56.410 --> 00:34:02.005
an immortality of fame.
And we would read -- can you

00:34:02.005 --> 00:34:06.557
imagine getting such a letter?
Milton may well blush at this

00:34:06.557 --> 00:34:10.453
extraordinary confession.
He is courting poetic fame more

00:34:10.453 --> 00:34:14.278
shamelessly at this point in his
career than he has before and

00:34:14.278 --> 00:34:18.124
perhaps that he will after.
The death of Edward King is

00:34:18.124 --> 00:34:22.271
really forcing him to question
the point of his pursuit of

00:34:22.271 --> 00:34:26.199
greatness, of poetic fame,
and all of his ambition.

00:34:26.199 --> 00:34:29.699
The poem continues at line
seventy:

00:34:29.699 --> 00:34:33.936
Fame is the spur that the
clear spirit doth raise

00:34:33.936 --> 00:34:38.320
(That last infirmity of Noble
mind) To scorn delights,

00:34:38.320 --> 00:34:42.469
and live laborious days,
But the fair Guerdon when we

00:34:42.469 --> 00:34:46.989
hope to find, And think to
burst out into sudden blaze,

00:34:46.989 --> 00:34:52.740
 Comes the blind Fury with
th'abhorred shears, And

00:34:52.740 --> 00:34:58.078
slits the thin-spun life.
It's the pursuit of fame,

00:34:58.078 --> 00:35:02.659
the noble pursuit of fame,
that spurs us to scorn delights

00:35:02.659 --> 00:35:07.249
and to live laborious days.
Fame spurs us to pursue the

00:35:07.249 --> 00:35:10.712
abstinent life of the poet.
It's the guerdon,

00:35:10.712 --> 00:35:14.320
the reward, the prize of fame
that we're continually

00:35:14.320 --> 00:35:18.211
anticipating will burst out
someday in a sudden blaze of

00:35:18.211 --> 00:35:21.299
glory.
But as soon as we hope to find

00:35:21.299 --> 00:35:23.531
that guerdon,
the golden ring,

00:35:23.531 --> 00:35:27.920
comes the blind Fury with the
abhorred shears -- ouch!

00:35:27.920 --> 00:35:33.182
-- and slits the thin-spun life.
The blind Fury here is the

00:35:33.182 --> 00:35:37.697
mythological figure Atropos;
this is the Fate that cuts the

00:35:37.697 --> 00:35:41.250
slender thread by which our
lives dangle.

00:35:41.250 --> 00:35:45.192
Milton lends a special horror,
I think, to this image of a

00:35:45.192 --> 00:35:49.343
blind Fury, and I hope you will
agree with those critics -- I

00:35:49.343 --> 00:35:53.078
didn't make this up -- who find
embedded in these lines

00:35:53.078 --> 00:35:57.159
something like a figurative
intimation of castration.

00:35:57.159 --> 00:36:01.618
Like the furious Bacchae,
the furious Atropos emasculates

00:36:01.618 --> 00:36:05.599
the man who dares to aspire to
poetic greatness.

00:36:05.599 --> 00:36:10.110
With the abhorred shears she
cruelly punishes the virgin poet

00:36:10.110 --> 00:36:14.770
for his failure on the one hand
to use the sexual body that God

00:36:14.770 --> 00:36:18.402
has endowed him with,
but you also have the image

00:36:18.402 --> 00:36:21.592
here of the poet's death.
You have the image of the

00:36:21.592 --> 00:36:25.139
cutting off, the castration,
of the power of generativity.

00:36:25.139 --> 00:36:29.515
All poetic potency,
all power to assert oneself in

00:36:29.515 --> 00:36:34.962
the world, can be severed and
that's it.I don't think that

00:36:34.962 --> 00:36:39.873
the critics who see here an
image of castration are just

00:36:39.873 --> 00:36:43.809
imagining it,
because there is such a weird

00:36:43.809 --> 00:36:47.670
and such a persistent interest
in the human body,

00:36:47.670 --> 00:36:51.527
and especially in the poet's
body, throughout this poem --

00:36:51.527 --> 00:36:56.005
Milton's focus on the body,
on the entire realm of the

00:36:56.005 --> 00:36:58.531
corporeal.
I'm hoping that it feels a

00:36:58.531 --> 00:37:00.891
little strange to you and it
seems strange,

00:37:00.891 --> 00:37:03.789
I think,
when you consider what is

00:37:03.789 --> 00:37:09.260
obviously here the Christian
context of Milton's "Lycidas."

00:37:09.260 --> 00:37:13.776
Orthodox Christianity teaches
us to put aside our concerns for

00:37:13.776 --> 00:37:16.590
the body when we consider our
death.

00:37:16.590 --> 00:37:21.304
The Old Testament prophet had
said, "All flesh is grass," an

00:37:21.304 --> 00:37:26.019
important verse for the new
dispensation of Christianity.

00:37:26.019 --> 00:37:29.646
The only thing that matters is
the salvation of the

00:37:29.646 --> 00:37:34.700
incorporeal, the bodiless soul,
but Milton is so unorthodox,

00:37:34.700 --> 00:37:39.072
or at least heterodox,
in his insistence on the

00:37:39.072 --> 00:37:44.393
importance of the body in this
poem.Look at the verse

00:37:44.393 --> 00:37:48.100
paragraph that begins at line
132.

00:37:48.100 --> 00:37:52.449
Oh, this passage!
Milton asks the Sicilian muse

00:37:52.449 --> 00:37:57.837
-- this is the muse of pastoral
poetry -- asks the muse to help

00:37:57.837 --> 00:38:01.400
him strew the flowers over the
hearse,

00:38:01.400 --> 00:38:06.330
to strew with flowers the
casket in which Lycidas' body

00:38:06.330 --> 00:38:08.710
lies.
The body of Lycidas,

00:38:08.710 --> 00:38:12.365
even in death,
is of an unusual interest to

00:38:12.365 --> 00:38:15.387
our poet.
The speaker employs -- this is

00:38:15.387 --> 00:38:18.354
an amazingly physical,
and I think it's even a

00:38:18.354 --> 00:38:21.842
sensual,
language as he catalogs the

00:38:21.842 --> 00:38:27.060
flowers that he imagines will
cover Lycidas' body.

00:38:27.060 --> 00:38:32.867
Line 135: 
Ye valleys low where the

00:38:32.867 --> 00:38:37.760
mild whispers use Of shades
and wanton winds and gushing

00:38:37.760 --> 00:38:41.289
brooks,
 On whose fresh lap the

00:38:41.289 --> 00:38:46.989
swart Star sparely looks,
Throw hither all your quaint

00:38:46.989 --> 00:38:51.057
enamell'd eyes,
 That on the green turf

00:38:51.057 --> 00:38:54.250
suck the honied
showers…

00:38:54.250 --> 00:38:58.130
Okay: maybe the Elder Brother
in Comus was wrong.

00:38:58.130 --> 00:39:01.259
The virgin's body can't -- you
remember that amazing

00:39:01.259 --> 00:39:04.449
counterfactual fantasy -- the
virgin's body can't,

00:39:04.449 --> 00:39:08.540
perhaps we're acknowledging
here, can't be transmuted into

00:39:08.540 --> 00:39:11.188
spirit or soul.
But we can still tend,

00:39:11.188 --> 00:39:13.329
and we can nurse,
the dead body.

00:39:13.329 --> 00:39:17.488
We can lovingly care for it and
ornament it here in our very

00:39:17.488 --> 00:39:21.455
corporeal way on earth.
It's an intensely erotic

00:39:21.455 --> 00:39:25.959
passage, this image of
decorating King's tomb with

00:39:25.959 --> 00:39:29.405
flowers.
And it's at the height of this

00:39:29.405 --> 00:39:34.113
vision of our floral decoration
of Lycidas' hearse that the

00:39:34.113 --> 00:39:37.280
speaker is suddenly caught up
short.

00:39:37.280 --> 00:39:42.030
Look at line 154.
We read line 154 and we realize

00:39:42.030 --> 00:39:45.603
we have been had.
We have just -- we've been

00:39:45.603 --> 00:39:48.112
sucked in.
We have just participated in

00:39:48.112 --> 00:39:51.110
one of the biggest cheats that
poetry can offer.

00:39:51.110 --> 00:39:57.667
"Ay me!"
he says as he realizes,

00:39:57.667 --> 00:40:00.880
of course, there will be no
flowers.

00:40:00.880 --> 00:40:02.930
There's not going to be a
hearse.

00:40:02.930 --> 00:40:04.770
Why not?
There's no body!

00:40:04.770 --> 00:40:08.810
There's no body to decorate.
What have we been thinking?

00:40:08.810 --> 00:40:12.369
Lycidas was drowned.
His remains are unrecoverable.

00:40:12.369 --> 00:40:16.788
This is a terrible moment of
realization on the part of the

00:40:16.788 --> 00:40:19.288
speaker.
Whilst thee the shores

00:40:19.288 --> 00:40:22.889
and sounding Seas Wash far
away, where'er thy bones are

00:40:22.889 --> 00:40:25.508
hurl'd,
 Whether beyond the stormy

00:40:25.508 --> 00:40:29.439
Hebrides, Where thou perhaps
under the whelming tide

00:40:29.439 --> 00:40:33.369
Visit'st the bottom of the
monstrous world…

00:40:33.369 --> 00:40:37.150
Milton's confronting here the
awful fact that Lycidas' bones

00:40:37.150 --> 00:40:40.803
-- they've been hurled to the
four corners of the sounding

00:40:40.803 --> 00:40:43.550
seas.
They could be anywhere.

00:40:43.550 --> 00:40:47.109
And as if that weren't terrible
enough a realization,

00:40:47.109 --> 00:40:51.284
he goes on to envision an even
more grotesque end for Lycidas'

00:40:51.284 --> 00:40:54.276
body.
He conjures -- surely this is

00:40:54.276 --> 00:40:58.633
indecorous.
This is wildly inappropriate,

00:40:58.633 --> 00:41:03.903
I think, in such a pious poem.
He conjures the indecorous

00:41:03.903 --> 00:41:07.806
image of the dead Lycidas under
the whelming tide visiting the

00:41:07.806 --> 00:41:11.128
bottom of the monstrous sea.
It's that word "visit" that

00:41:11.128 --> 00:41:13.924
gets me every time.
It's so inappropriate and

00:41:13.924 --> 00:41:17.246
ghoulish, I think,
in this already sufficiently

00:41:17.246 --> 00:41:19.483
ghoulish context.
First of all,

00:41:19.483 --> 00:41:23.024
it's like a parody of the epic
journey to the underworld

00:41:23.024 --> 00:41:26.260
that we have in so many
great classical texts,

00:41:26.260 --> 00:41:30.134
and it forces us to think,
at least for a moment here,

00:41:30.134 --> 00:41:33.423
of Lycidas as some ghastly
underwater visitor:

00:41:33.423 --> 00:41:36.671
a skeletal,
monstrous version of Jacques

00:41:36.671 --> 00:41:40.360
Cousteau peering into the
unknowable monstrous,

00:41:40.360 --> 00:41:45.367
mysterious depths of the bottom
of the world.This intensely

00:41:45.367 --> 00:41:50.375
intimate focus on the human body
is out of place in a Christian

00:41:50.375 --> 00:41:54.289
elegy and this,
of course, Milton knows.

00:41:54.289 --> 00:41:58.158
It's because the investment in
the bodily world is so great

00:41:58.158 --> 00:42:02.159
here that Milton ultimately
turns to the Christian vision,

00:42:02.159 --> 00:42:06.590
the more familiar Christian
vision, of a bodiless afterlife.

00:42:06.590 --> 00:42:10.084
This is how this logic goes --
we are all familiar with this:

00:42:10.084 --> 00:42:13.638
our body remains to molder in
the earth or welter in the ocean

00:42:13.638 --> 00:42:16.637
(where'ere),
but our incorporeal spirit

00:42:16.637 --> 00:42:20.296
rises to heaven where it can
enjoy an ethereal,

00:42:20.296 --> 00:42:23.730
a bodiless,
world of eternity.

00:42:23.730 --> 00:42:27.485
And so Milton concludes
"Lycidas" with this standard

00:42:27.485 --> 00:42:32.394
vision of Christian consolation.
On some level this is textbook

00:42:32.394 --> 00:42:35.360
Protestant or Catholic
Christianity.

00:42:35.360 --> 00:42:38.264
Weep no more,
woeful Shepherds weep no

00:42:38.264 --> 00:42:41.440
more For Lycidas your sorrow
is not dead,

00:42:41.440 --> 00:42:45.881
 Sunk though he be beneath
the wat'ry floor, So sinks

00:42:45.881 --> 00:42:51.138
the day-star in the Ocean bed,
 And yet anon repairs his

00:42:51.138 --> 00:42:55.554
drooping head.
This image of the afterlife is

00:42:55.554 --> 00:42:59.039
founded on the orthodox figure
for eternity.

00:42:59.039 --> 00:43:02.625
The body stays to the earth
while the soul,

00:43:02.625 --> 00:43:05.869
like the day-star,
rises to the sky.

00:43:05.869 --> 00:43:09.639
But when you look a little more
closely at this conclusion,

00:43:09.639 --> 00:43:13.019
I think you realize that
Milton's heaven is almost as

00:43:13.019 --> 00:43:16.789
invested in the human body as
Milton's earth had been.

00:43:16.789 --> 00:43:19.849
The heaven imagined here is
able actually to supply us,

00:43:19.849 --> 00:43:23.250
in fact, with a better body
than the one we had down here.

00:43:23.250 --> 00:43:25.030
When the speaker writes that
the day-star "…

00:43:25.030 --> 00:43:30.446
yet anon repairs his drooping
head," we are reminded of

00:43:30.446 --> 00:43:33.353
Orpheus.
We have an image here of the

00:43:33.353 --> 00:43:36.346
reconstituted,
repaired body of Orpheus whose

00:43:36.346 --> 00:43:39.135
gory,
severed head had been sent down

00:43:39.135 --> 00:43:41.960
the swift Hebrus to the Lesbian
shore.

00:43:41.960 --> 00:43:45.413
It's as if Milton can't let go
of this most un-Christian

00:43:45.413 --> 00:43:49.526
attachment to the human body.
I think it's fair to say that

00:43:49.526 --> 00:43:53.786
Milton can't really imagine or
fully invest himself in the

00:43:53.786 --> 00:43:57.821
Christian heaven until he can
fully corporealize it and

00:43:57.821 --> 00:44:00.217
imagine it bodily.
This is exactly,

00:44:00.217 --> 00:44:02.250
of course, what he will do in
Paradise Lost.

00:44:02.250 --> 00:44:06.860
Everyone in Milton's heaven
has a body, even God Himself.

00:44:06.860 --> 00:44:10.059
God Himself in Paradise Lost
is nothing but body.

00:44:10.059 --> 00:44:13.377
His body is the universe
itself.Listen to the

00:44:13.377 --> 00:44:17.524
physicality of the rest of the
description of Milton's heaven

00:44:17.524 --> 00:44:20.980
in "Lycidas." This
is line 172:

00:44:20.980 --> 00:44:24.340
So Lycidas,
sunk low, but mounted high,

00:44:24.340 --> 00:44:28.119
Through the dear might of him
that walk'd the waves,

00:44:28.119 --> 00:44:32.323
 Where other groves,
and other streams along,

00:44:32.323 --> 00:44:35.800
With Nectar pure his oozy locks
he laves,

00:44:35.800 --> 00:44:40.693
 And hears the unexpressive
nuptial Song, In the blest

00:44:40.693 --> 00:44:45.108
Kingdoms meek of joy and love.
There entertain him all the

00:44:45.108 --> 00:44:49.079
Saints above, In solemn
troops, and sweet Societies

00:44:49.079 --> 00:44:52.541
That sing,
and singing in their glory

00:44:52.541 --> 00:44:58.179
move And wipe the tears
forever from his eyes.

00:44:58.179 --> 00:45:03.388
Clearly, the other groves and
the other streams are different

00:45:03.388 --> 00:45:06.044
in heaven.
They are different from the

00:45:06.044 --> 00:45:09.393
groves and streams we have down
here, but they don't seem

00:45:09.393 --> 00:45:12.383
necessarily to differ,
I submit, in their degree of

00:45:12.383 --> 00:45:15.025
physicality.
Lycidas is going to shampoo his

00:45:15.025 --> 00:45:17.803
hair in heaven much as he
shampooed his hair on earth,

00:45:17.803 --> 00:45:20.320
except in heaven there's always
a difference.

00:45:20.320 --> 00:45:26.699
It will be a nectar pure with
which he laves his oozy locks.

00:45:26.699 --> 00:45:29.975
And even more important,
Lycidas will continue to sing

00:45:29.975 --> 00:45:32.510
in heaven just as he had sung on
earth,

00:45:32.510 --> 00:45:36.603
except now he can hear the
unexpressive -- that means

00:45:36.603 --> 00:45:41.429
"inexpressible" -- nuptial song.
We remember this song.

00:45:41.429 --> 00:45:45.003
This is the song mentioned in
Revelation 14 that Milton is

00:45:45.003 --> 00:45:48.577
continually alluding to and we
saw him allude to just this

00:45:48.577 --> 00:45:52.355
passage in "Ad Patrem."
John the Divine had written in

00:45:52.355 --> 00:45:56.055
Revelation 14 -- you know this:
And they sung as it were

00:45:56.055 --> 00:45:57.789
a new song before the
throne…

00:45:57.789 --> 00:46:00.808
and no man could learn that
song but the one hundred and

00:46:00.808 --> 00:46:03.661
forty and four thousand,
which were redeemed from the

00:46:03.661 --> 00:46:07.025
earth.
These are they which were

00:46:07.025 --> 00:46:12.079
not defiled with women;
for they are virgins.

00:46:12.079 --> 00:46:15.369
And it's virgins who get to
sing the nuptial song at the

00:46:15.369 --> 00:46:18.179
wedding of the lamb that John
also envisions.

00:46:18.179 --> 00:46:21.768
Milton can't allow himself to
embrace the wonderful fiction,

00:46:21.768 --> 00:46:25.236
that beautiful fiction that had
been espoused by the Elder

00:46:25.236 --> 00:46:28.460
Brother: the fantasy that
virgins don't even die,

00:46:28.460 --> 00:46:31.315
that their bodies are simply
reconstituted somehow [laughs]

00:46:31.315 --> 00:46:34.659
as angelic spirits.
That went too far.

00:46:34.659 --> 00:46:39.110
It was too pagan,
way too unorthodox.

00:46:39.110 --> 00:46:43.725
But Milton does permit himself
the closest scriptural version

00:46:43.725 --> 00:46:47.178
of that fiction,
and that's John's image in

00:46:47.178 --> 00:46:51.554
Revelation 14 of the special
heavenly rewards for virgin

00:46:51.554 --> 00:46:56.407
poets.Now you also looked at
for today the Latin poem that

00:46:56.407 --> 00:47:00.783
Milton wrote not long after
"Lycidas." That's the

00:47:00.783 --> 00:47:04.768
poem "Damon's Epitaph,"
the "Epitaphium Damonis,"

00:47:04.768 --> 00:47:07.679
written on the very sad
occasion of the death of

00:47:07.679 --> 00:47:10.775
Milton's best friend,
Charles Diodati,

00:47:10.775 --> 00:47:14.010
who died the next year,
1638.

00:47:14.010 --> 00:47:18.291
You remember this is the young
fellow that Milton had confessed

00:47:18.291 --> 00:47:21.610
his desire for immortal fame to.
Look at the end of that poem.

00:47:21.610 --> 00:47:23.550
This is page 139 in the
Hughes.

00:47:23.550 --> 00:47:28.287
This is where Milton
imagines -- you have to turn to

00:47:28.287 --> 00:47:31.401
this.
He imagines Diodati just as he

00:47:31.401 --> 00:47:35.922
had imagined Edward King,
enjoying at last his heavenly

00:47:35.922 --> 00:47:38.800
reward.
This is the English translation

00:47:38.800 --> 00:47:42.868
because the poem is in Latin:
Because you loved the

00:47:42.868 --> 00:47:47.449
blush of modesty and a stainless
youth and because you did not

00:47:47.449 --> 00:47:50.229
taste the delight of the
marriage-bed,

00:47:50.229 --> 00:47:53.210
lo!
the rewards of virginity are

00:47:53.210 --> 00:47:56.928
reserved for you.
Your glorious head shall be

00:47:56.928 --> 00:48:01.874
bound with a shining crown and
with shadowing fronds of joyous

00:48:01.874 --> 00:48:06.819
palms in your hands you shall
enact your part eternally in the

00:48:06.819 --> 00:48:11.846
immortal marriage where song and
the sound of the lyre [can you

00:48:11.846 --> 00:48:14.683
even believe what I'm about to
say?]

00:48:14.683 --> 00:48:19.142
are mingled in ecstasy with
blessed dances and where the

00:48:19.142 --> 00:48:24.250
festal orgies rage under the
heavenly thyrsus.

00:48:24.250 --> 00:48:27.365
Now we recognize the song.
This is the song from

00:48:27.365 --> 00:48:30.800
Revelation of the virgins who
could learn and sing the new

00:48:30.800 --> 00:48:33.090
song before the throne of the
Lord,

00:48:33.090 --> 00:48:38.309
but Milton has obviously taken
John's image here and exploded

00:48:38.309 --> 00:48:42.050
the implications of its erotic
potential.

00:48:42.050 --> 00:48:47.401
It's not just that virgins are
entitled to sing a heavenly song

00:48:47.401 --> 00:48:51.833
as Milton is saying Diodati is.
The heavenly reward in this

00:48:51.833 --> 00:48:55.001
poem involves all of the
sensuality, all of the sensual

00:48:55.001 --> 00:48:58.170
experience, that was denied and
repressed on earth.

00:48:58.170 --> 00:49:00.741
This [laughs]
-- "Damon's Epitaph"

00:49:00.741 --> 00:49:04.813
ends with a virtual orgasm
of Christian consolation as

00:49:04.813 --> 00:49:09.242
Milton gives his best friend the
most unbelievable sendoff that

00:49:09.242 --> 00:49:13.118
is possible to give.
The heaven in this poem is so

00:49:13.118 --> 00:49:17.016
far from being the incorporeal
-- the spiritual heaven of

00:49:17.016 --> 00:49:21.610
orthodox Christianity that you
have an image of an actual orgy,

00:49:21.610 --> 00:49:26.382
the festal orgy raging under
the thyrsus (that's the phallic

00:49:26.382 --> 00:49:28.050
wand).
Who's holding this wand?

00:49:28.050 --> 00:49:30.939
Presumably none other than the
orgiastic leader,

00:49:30.939 --> 00:49:33.414
God himself.
There's no other way to

00:49:33.414 --> 00:49:36.712
interpret these lines which,
as you can imagine,

00:49:36.712 --> 00:49:39.380
critics simply pretend don't
exist,

00:49:39.380 --> 00:49:42.190
[laughs]
because who can figure out what

00:49:42.190 --> 00:49:46.010
to say?In "Lycidas" Milton
doesn't let himself,

00:49:46.010 --> 00:49:50.867
thank God, go quite so far as
he does in this amazing ending

00:49:50.867 --> 00:49:55.643
to "Damon's Epitaph." In
fact nowhere else do we see

00:49:55.643 --> 00:50:00.254
Milton literally [laughs]
bursting out at the seams as he

00:50:00.254 --> 00:50:03.851
seems to in this poem.
But the unmistakable

00:50:03.851 --> 00:50:07.143
physicality of the heaven
imagined in the poem about

00:50:07.143 --> 00:50:11.111
Diodati gives us some idea,
I think, of how to read the end

00:50:11.111 --> 00:50:14.257
of "Lycidas." The
corporeality of "Damon's

00:50:14.257 --> 00:50:18.321
Epitaph" illuminates we
can see the unorthodox direction

00:50:18.321 --> 00:50:22.253
in which Milton's "Lycidas" is
tending.So let me conclude

00:50:22.253 --> 00:50:25.210
here.
Milton has wrenched this poem

00:50:25.210 --> 00:50:28.802
away from Christianity,
and he's forced it into a

00:50:28.802 --> 00:50:32.469
direction that we could loosely
call paganism.

00:50:32.469 --> 00:50:35.454
There has been a slippage from
Christian spirituality into

00:50:35.454 --> 00:50:38.229
something like a pagan
naturalism, and it's a world in

00:50:38.229 --> 00:50:40.838
which all things are physical.
All spirits,

00:50:40.838 --> 00:50:43.670
like the genius loci,
are physical,

00:50:43.670 --> 00:50:46.639
palpable presences in the
natural world.

00:50:46.639 --> 00:50:50.062
The human body,
the world of flesh and blood

00:50:50.062 --> 00:50:53.962
that we all inhabit,
has in some way at the end of

00:50:53.962 --> 00:50:58.875
this poem reasserted itself.
In this final assertion of the

00:50:58.875 --> 00:51:02.265
body Milton, I think,
is able to recover his

00:51:02.265 --> 00:51:07.469
theodicy, his attempt to justify
the ways of God here on earth.

00:51:07.469 --> 00:51:13.510
Milton's Lycidas' body is still
in some way a physical one.

00:51:13.510 --> 00:51:16.483
To the extent that Lycidas'
body has been recovered,

00:51:16.483 --> 00:51:19.558
that it's been redeemed,
Milton is able -- perhaps

00:51:19.558 --> 00:51:22.178
successfully,
Milton is able to justify the

00:51:22.178 --> 00:51:25.878
ways of God to men.
He's able to justify the ways

00:51:25.878 --> 00:51:30.293
of God to men here on the
physical -- on this intimately

00:51:30.293 --> 00:51:35.030
bodily earth.This is the
last thing I will tell you.

00:51:35.030 --> 00:51:39.806
As you have no doubt
experienced, this is a dense and

00:51:39.806 --> 00:51:44.030
difficult poem,
so please reread it innumerable

00:51:44.030 --> 00:51:48.748
times for Wednesday's class,
and in addition to that do the

00:51:48.748 --> 00:51:51.000
other readings assigned.
Okay.

